Brazos County now represented a perfect 
district, population-wise. At first glance, one

34:01.091 --> 34:15.291
would think this would make it quite simple,

34:01.091 --> 34:15.291
but having a county with the exact population 
required for a legislative district does create

34:15.524 --> 34:16.725
problems. It removes flexibility that the 
writers of the redistricting bill would like to

34:18.647 --> 34:36.606
have in working with districts that surround the 
county with the right population. I know Brazos

34:37.707 --> 34:45.075
County was the only county that had such a 
population. The fact of Brazos County having a

34:46.439 --> 35:03.239
perfect population meant that two incumbent 
colleagues in the legislature just west of Brazos

34:46.439 --> 35:03.239
County ended up being paired. And the legislator 
to the east had some difficulty in getting the kind

35:04.020 --> 35:10.388
of district that he wanted. In the 1981 session, we 
once again met the challenge of constitutional

35:11.465 --> 35:21.198
amendment to the permanent university fund. 
There was an effort to rewrite the higher

35:22.540 --> 35:40.965
education portion of the constitution

35:22.540 --> 35:40.965
to deal primarily with the issue of how the schools 
outside of the permanent university fund are

35:22.540 --> 35:40.965
provided their construction funding.

35:45.360 --> 35:51.369
They had been using the 10 cent tax, i.e. 10 cents on 
a $100 valuation,

35:51.389 --> 36:02.886
to generate the revenues used by schools outside 
of the permanent university fund. There was a

36:04.823 --> 36:21.688
challenge to this fund as being 
unconstitutional, and it was one that we were

36:04.823 --> 36:21.688
likely to lose in the courts, thereby leaving 
these schools with no source of funds.

36:25.234 --> 36:29.380
Amendments are required to get 100 votes.

36:31.975 --> 36:42.766
An amendment to the proposal was offered to put 
Prairie View into the Permanent University Fund

36:31.975 --> 36:42.766
for 1-6. I

36:42.986 --> 36:59.383
felt like this was not

36:42.986 --> 36:59.383
in our best interest since Prairie View was 
actually over-built at the time and A&M was

36:42.986 --> 36:59.383
under-built. And to put a formula in the 
Constitution did not

37:00.241 --> 37:08.014
sense.

37:10.838 --> 37:18.551
I was defeated with regards to the amendment since 
it took only a majority vote. But I was able to

37:19.653 --> 37:26.063
garner enough votes in opposition to the 
amendment to keep it from getting the necessary

37:26.802 --> 37:31.386
100 votes required to pass. That brought a call 
from Governor Clements to meet in his office and

37:33.248 --> 37:40.514
discuss the issue. Governor Clements proceeded 
to advise me that Prairie View had not been treated

37:42.095 --> 37:56.708
fairly and started giving examples of 
construction items that had not been funded at

37:42.095 --> 37:56.708
Prairie View. I proceeded to point out to Governor 
Clements that all of the construction items that

37:58.392 --> 38:12.949
he had mentioned were items that only the 
legislature could provide the funds and not the

37:58.392 --> 38:12.949
A&M System Board of Regents. It is difficult to win 
an argument with the governor and particularly

38:14.311 --> 38:20.518
Governor Clements, I think I was able to persuade 
him that we were not going to give in on the issue and

38:20.954 --> 38:29.683
that there had to be some other resolution.

38:32.406 --> 38:42.877
The session adjourned without addressing the 
question of education funding in the

38:32.406 --> 38:42.877
Constitution. The issues that I have dealt with 
during my legislative years, the one that I caught

38:50.030 --> 39:01.121
the most flack from my colleagues was the one 
dealing with the teacher retirement system.

39:03.183 --> 39:19.378
Prior to the session in 1981, I had asked the 
Legislative Budget Board to consider what the

39:03.183 --> 39:19.378
ramifications would be if we passed a statute that 
required the teacher's retirement system to

39:19.865 --> 39:27.017
implement the rule of 85. The rule of 85 being that 
if your years toward retirement and your age

39:27.518 --> 39:42.244
totaled to be 85, you could draw full retirement. 
This was the system that was used in the state

39:43.203 --> 39:54.700
employee's retirement system, and I had had 
requests for this to be applied to the teacher

39:43.203 --> 39:54.700
retirement system. I quickly learned that the 
Legislative Budget Board did not get very good

39:56.503 --> 40:09.042
information from the teacher retirement system, 
and this had been a real problem.

40:11.823 --> 40:28.608
This request of mine gave them the impetus to seek 
information from outside sources regarding the

40:11.823 --> 40:28.608
viability of the teacher retirement system. The 
result of the study the Legislative Budget Board

40:29.870 --> 40:38.944
made, it was determined that the teacher 
retirement system could use their requirement

40:41.253 --> 40:54.449
for general revenue appropriations by $217 
million and still be the most viable retirement

40:41.253 --> 40:54.449
system in the nation. The budget board met just 
prior to the legislative session.

41:00.997 --> 41:08.847
It was decided to go ahead and expend those funds 
through the appropriations process on the

41:08.962 --> 41:20.655
assumption that a bill would be passed that would 
reduce the money flowing into the teacher's

41:08.962 --> 41:20.655
retirement system by $217 million. I had made all 
kinds of compromises with the teacher retirement

41:22.397 --> 41:30.506
system to get the bill passed. The Retired 
Teachers Association, they continued to hammer

41:30.846 --> 41:35.391
away on their own legislators to the point it was 
extremely difficult to get the bill passed.

41:47.288 --> 42:00.949
Members that supported me on the issue to get it 
passed apparently heard from their retirees into

41:47.288 --> 42:00.949
the teacher retirement system for years to come. 
In 1981, Ross Perot was heading up a program called

42:05.645 --> 42:13.676
War on Drugs. This was to get some bills passed in 
the legislature that would help curb the drug

42:13.697 --> 42:21.548
traffic in Texas. I met with Mr. Perot

42:22.830 --> 42:35.027
prior to the session in College Station here and 
was supportive of what he was trying to do.

42:38.129 --> 42:52.808
He had asked me to carry several of the bills, but I 
declined on a basis that, as chairman of the House

42:38.129 --> 42:52.808
Appropriations Committee, I just did not have the 
time to carry additional bills. But I would help in

42:54.069 --> 43:01.278
every way that I could to see that, to help get the 
bills passed through the legislature. I asked him

43:03.021 --> 43:07.326
to take to a friend of mine And I told this friend I 
would help him with it. It was a bill that required a

43:12.062 --> 43:25.780
triplicate prescription of all drugs that were 
considered dangerous. I had a bill in the

43:26.080 --> 43:35.052
Appropriations Committee to make Martin Luther 
King's birthday a holiday. The members of the

43:36.685 --> 43:45.259
committee were not supportive at all of this bill, 
and I knew that the votes were not there. I did want

43:47.082 --> 43:53.413
to do something with regards to holidays because 
it had been something somewhat controversial.

43:55.756 --> 44:02.187
I kept telling the author of the Martin Luther King 
birthday bill that I... was working on something

44:03.280 --> 44:31.870
and that i would uh... give him a hearing at the time 
i got the other bill worked up and i found out that he

44:03.280 --> 44:31.870
was uh... not letting the triplicate 
prescription bill come out of his committee even

44:03.280 --> 44:31.870
though the votes in the committee were there the 
triplicate prescription bill uh... was a concept

44:03.280 --> 44:31.870
that would hopefully reduce dangerous drugs by a 
considerable amount. Finally, the author of the

44:38.592 --> 44:47.648
bill brought the speaker to my desk and said, we 
want to get the bill out of committee. And I said,

44:48.489 --> 44:54.700
fine, I'll give you a hearing on your bill if you'll 
pass out the triplicate prescription bill. His

44:56.783 --> 44:58.566
reaction was, no way. that lasted about ten 
seconds, and he came back and said, okay, it's a

44:59.727 --> 45:03.953
deal. So I attempted to get his bill out once he had 
passed the triplicate prescription bill out, and

45:05.555 --> 45:19.794
of course I could not get the bill, necessary votes 
to pass the bill. Understand that the triplicate

45:21.897 --> 45:29.667
prescription bill has reduced drug trafficking 
by a significant amount. 1981 was one of the first

45:30.676 --> 45:36.764
years we had to deal with teachers' pay in the 
Appropriations Committee.

45:39.809 --> 45:51.064
We're falling behind in their pay because of the 
high rate of inflation and the fact that teachers

45:39.809 --> 45:51.064
have always been underpaid. One thing that I 
wanted to avoid was the bill

46:02.722 --> 46:05.968
more funds than the comptroller could certify. 
The member who was handling the education portion

46:07.752 --> 46:18.233
of the appropriations bill made a proposal to 
provide a 28.5% increase for school teachers. I

46:24.934 --> 46:33.743
knew what the fiscal implications were and did not 
support his proposal. Consequently, it was

46:35.685 --> 46:37.186
killed.

46:40.450 --> 46:48.118
The speaker immediately contacted me and said 
that was his proposal and He wanted it brought up. I

46:49.858 --> 46:51.202
said, we don't have the money. He said, I've got the 
money for you. I said, okay, if you assure me we've

46:53.910 --> 47:01.492
got the money for you, I'll find a way to bring it 
back up and we'll get it passed. So after a few

47:01.512 --> 47:03.357
hours, it passed.

